ownedComment.body: Place extensions in the Extension package

To create new DATEX II model elements in Enterprise Architect, use the "UML Profile for DATEX II", under "UML Profiles" in the "Resources" tab.
For D2Relation or D2LevelBExtension: click on the D2Relation or D2LevelBExtension stereotype in the DATEX UML profile tree in the “Resources” tab. Then with that still highlighted, drag between two classes in a class diagram to create a new D2Relation or D2LevelBExtension.
For all other kinds of model element in the DATEX II UML profile: drag the relevant stereotype from the profile onto the class diagram.
If you use another way, this may look correct in diagrams, but Enterprise Architect may not associate your elements with the correct DATEX II stereotypes, leading to problems if you use DATEX II tools to process your model.
(You can also create plain UML generalization elements, which do not have a DATEX II stereotype.)
As the NetworkManagement class is abstract, it must be specialised if the extension for EnhancedReroutingManagement is used (for example by using GeneralNetworkManagement of type 'other').
For further aggregations of RouteInformation see also previous figure.
As the OperatorAction class is abstract, it must be specialised if the extension for SignSetting is used (for example by using GeneralNetworkManagement of type 'other').

An action implementing a Traffic Management Plan refers to the TMP activation Service Request and may refer to a predefined or non predefined Traffic Management Plan request, so one information attribute among non-predefined or predefined is to be provided besides the reference to the service request for which the Operator Action had been implemented.
As the OperatorAction class is abstract, it must be specialised if this extension is used (for example by using GeneralNetworkManagement of type 'other').

NOTE: here Operator Action referring to situation publication model allows optionally to specify exactly in the table the Action which has to be implemented with all implementation details, but as Situation Record specialisation Operator Action has Validity information which have some mandatory items like Start Date Time which are not applicable in the table as definition of Operation to be implemented. So Validity Start Date Time have to be considered only after specific application level agreement.

NOTE: here Operator Action referring to situation publication model allows optionally to specify exactly in the table the Action which has to be implemented with all implementation details, but as Situation Record specialisation Operator Action has Validity information which have some mandatory items like Start Date Time which are not applicable in the table as definition of Operation to be implemented. So Validity Start Date Time have to be considered only after specific application level agreement.

Within each instance of this class, specific enumerated values can only be used once for all attributes. E.g. applicableMonth can only contain “january” once. A combination of applicableDay “monday” and “tuesday” and applicableMonth “may” and “june” results in a data set of all Mondays and Tuesday in May and June.
When using this class, at least one "applicableDay" must be specified in class "DayWeekMonth".
As the Raodworks class is abstract, it must be specialised if the extension for StreetWorks is used (for example by using MaintenanceWorks of type 'other').
"minimumCarOccupancy" is only valid if "roadOrCarriagewayOrLaneManagementType" is set to "carPoolLaneInOperation".
As the Raodworks class is abstract, it must be specialised if the extension for StreetWorks is used (for example by using MaintenanceWorks of type 'other').
